    explanation: 'Overall explanation Incorrect Answers: A. Update the model monitoring job to use a lower sampling rate. Might reduce the frequency of alerts by sampling less data for comparison, but it does not address the root cause of the skew and could potentially lead to missing important discrepancies between training and serving data. C. Temporarily disable the alert. Enable the alert again after a sufficient amount of new production traffic has passed through the Vertex AI endpoint. D. Temporarily disable the alert until the model can be retrained again on newer training data. Retrain the model again after a sufficient amount of new production traffic has passed through the Vertex AI endpoint. Are not proactive solutions. Disabling alerts does not solve the underlying problem of training-serving skew and may result in the model continuing to perform poorly on production traffic without generating necessary alerts for action. Correct Answer B. Update the model monitoring job to use the more recent training data that was used to retrain the model. This action ensures that the model monitoring job is comparing the production traffic against the same distribution of data that the model was most recently trained on. Training-serving skew occurs when the statistical properties of the data seen by the model in production differ significantly from the properties of the data on which the model was trained. By updating the model monitoring job to reflect the most recent training data, you align the baseline used for monitoring with the current state of the model, allowing for more accurate detection of skews.'
